cs.NE, cs.RO, cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.AI 

The paper focuses on building spiking neural networks for mobile robotic applications, specifically for controlling a lane-keeping vehicle using event-based neuromorphic vision sensors. This involves training the SNNs using both indirect and direct end-to-end methods. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). The paper also involves robotics (cs.RO), computer vision (cs.CV), machine learning (cs.LG), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) as the methods used involve deep Q-learning and reward-modulated spike-timing-dependent plasticity.
